[2]
Date: Fri 14 May 2004 2:40 PM
From: Dave Halvorson DVM, ACPV


[David Halvorson kindly provided the following explanation of avian
influenza strains:]

For all avian influenza viruses, the H type only tells you about a single
gene in the virus. There are countless H6s floating around the western
hemisphere in the wild bird reservoir. Because recombination takes place in
the wild, it is impossible to determine the relatedness between any 2 H6
viruses without looking at all the genes. 2 viruses could have identical
H6s but have all 7 other genes be unique; and 2 viruses could have all the
other 7 genes identical but have different Hs. So it is possible for a H6
virus to be more closely related to a H9 (if it had 7 identical genes for
example) than another H6.

If the virus from the geese had subtyped as H5N1, it still would not have
had anything to so with the Asian H5N1.

We (the U.S.) have detected low-path H5 quite a few times in the last few
years (CA, MN, MI, TX [prior to 2004]), but these viruses had nothing to do
with Asian H5. Nonetheless, only MN avoided destroying the birds.

In our experience, all low-path AI viruses are a definite or potential
threat to domestic poultry. Because of immunosuppression, it's not unheard
of for mortality due to secondary infection to exceed 10 percent of a flock
infected with low-path AI. In the case of egg layers a production drop is
to be expected with any AI infection.

--
David Halvorson, DVM, ACPV
Extension Veterinarian - Avian Health
College Of Veterinary Medicine
University of Minnesota
1971 Commonwealth Avenue
Saint Paul, Minnesota 55108

