[3]
Date: Friday, May 14, 2004 2:35 PM
From: Whiting, Terry (MAFRI)
Source: Canadian Food Inspection Agency 13 May 2004 Press Release [edited]
<http://www.inspection.gc.ca/english/corpaffr/newcom/2004/20040513e.shtml>


Geese on British Columbia farm not infected with H5 Avian Influenza
-------------------------
Further testing has revealed that geese on a Fraser Valley farm were not
infected with either H5 or H7 avian influenza. There is strong evidence
indicating the geese were exposed to the H6 avian influenza virus. The H6
virus is not associated with serious animal or human illness.

Initial investigation gave cause for suspicion of an H5 infection on the
farm. Further testing revealed with greater certainty that there was no H5
or H7 infection in the geese but rather a strong indication of exposure to
H6. Additional tests currently underway may further define the virus type
in the geese. Further testing will also determine the type of virus present
in the ducks on the farm.

The flock was located within 3 kilometers of 3 known infected premises and
was targeted for depopulation as part of the CFIA's avian influenza
response. The regional depopulation of animals in response to contagious
diseases such as avian influenza reflects internationally accepted animal
disease management strategies.

Detecting various subtypes of the avian influenza virus is not surprising,
particularly in birds such as geese and ducks that are usually raised
outdoors. Under such conditions, commercial birds would have contact with
wild birds, which are known to carry various subtypes of the virus. Most
subtypes carried by wild birds are low pathogenic and do not cause serious
illness in birds. Neither clinical signs nor high mortality were observed
in this flock.

Bringing the spread of avian influenza to a halt is a priority for the
Government of Canada. All required resources are being made available to
aggressively protect the health of British Columbia's poultry industry.

END of CFIA Notice

Terry Whiting's Comment:

It is unfortunate that this finding of historic evidence (serology) of
another LPAI in circulation in outdoor birds was expected, and that
expectation was not communicated to the public through early media
contacts. Minnesota's experience with outdoor turkeys over the past 25
years has been the isolation of a different LPAI every year, especially in
the period preceding 1985 after which time the industry began moving to
indoor rearing.

This Canadian example where a school was evacuated in response to the
laboratory results, demonstrates abhorrent risk communication between the
veterinary scientific community and the human health scientific communities.

As we move forward with continental AI surveillance, as I expect will
happen, we will isolate numbers of LPAI from healthy poultry directly in
proportion to the funding that Governments make available [to conduct these
tests]. What we can't afford is the public and media hysteria generated by
non-scientifically justified responses to those normal no-risk isolations.

My faith that government administrators will respond with science-based
decisions is not strengthened by current activities by North American
players reacting to commercial opportunities presented by BSE.

References Turkey AI:

Pomeroy BS. (1981) Avian Influenza in the USA (1964-1981) Proceedings of
the International Symposium on Avian Influenza. Pp13-17 (Re-published by
USAHA AAAP on CD in Avian Diseases Vol 47 2003)

Pomeroy BS. (1986) Avian Influenza in Turkeys in the USA (1981-86)
Proceedings of the 2nd International Symposium on Avian Influenza. Pp14-21
(Re-published by USAHA AAAP on CD in Avian Diseases Vol 47 2003)

Pearson JE, Senne DA, Panigrahy B. (1992) Avian Influenza in the Western
Hemisphere including the Pacific Rim 1986-1992 Proceedings of the 3rd
International Symposium on Avian Influenza. Pp22-31

Pearson JE, Senne DA, Panigrahy B. (1997) Avian Influenza in the Western
Hemisphere including the Pacific Rim 1986-1996 Proceedings of the 4th
International Symposium on Avian Influenza. Pp 14-17

